  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. Key Federal Laws:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money Laundering)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Engaging in Monetary Transactions in Criminally Derived Property)\n\n3. State Statutes:\n- Many states have their own money laundering laws that complement federal legislation\n\n4. International Cooperation:\n- The U.S. works with international organizations like FATF (Financial Action Task Force) to combat money laundering\n\nThese statutes generally:\n- Define money laundering\n- Establish reporting requirements\n- Create criminal penalties\n- Mandate compliance procedures for financial institutions\n- Provide mechanisms for investigating and prosecuting money laundering activities\n\nPenalties can include significant fines and imprisonment for individuals and organizations found guilty of money laundering.",
